<?xml-stylesheet type="text/xsl" href="../assets/xml/rss.xsl" media="all"?><rss version="2.0" xmlns:dc="http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/" xmlns:atom="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom"><channel><title>Gopinath A R (mypaint)</title><link>https://g-ar.github.io/</link><description></description><atom:link href="https://g-ar.github.io/categories/mypaint.xml" rel="self" type="application/rss+xml"></atom:link><language>en</language><lastBuildDate>Sat, 24 Sep 2016 10:41:13 GMT</lastBuildDate><generator>https://getnikola.com/</generator><docs>http://blogs.law.harvard.edu/tech/rss</docs><item><title>Simulating mouse movement to draw in mypaint</title><link>https://g-ar.github.io/posts/simulating-mouse-movement-to-draw-in-mypaint/</link><dc:creator>Gopinath</dc:creator><description>&lt;div&gt;&lt;p&gt;Wouldn't it be nice if we can command where to move the mouse pointer and press buttons, and then use the functionality to draw in a painting program? We can do exactly that in systems running &lt;tt class="docutils literal"&gt;xorg&lt;/tt&gt; display server, by using &lt;tt class="docutils literal"&gt;xdotool&lt;/tt&gt; to simulate mouse and keyboard.&lt;/p&gt;
